Description: CVE-2026-5773 - Fix wrong reuse of SMB connection across different shares
 libcurl incorrectly reused SMB connections across different shares due to
 the connkeep() call in smb_connect(). This could result in downloading the
 wrong file or uploading to the wrong location when using identical
 credentials and server names but different shares. The upstream fix
 (curl 8.20.0) removes PROTOPT_CONN_REUSE from SMB protocol handlers in
 lib/protocol.c. In curl 7.88.1, the equivalent mechanism is the
 connkeep() call in lib/smb.c which is replaced with connclose() to
 disable SMB connection reuse entirely.
Origin: backport, https://github.com/curl/curl/commit/74a169575d6412dc0ff532acdf94de35a6c2a571
Author: Daniel Stenberg <daniel@haxx.se>
Last-Update: 2026-05-02

--- a/lib/smb.c
+++ b/lib/smb.c
@@ -267,8 +267,8 @@
   if(!smbc->recv_buf)
     return CURLE_OUT_OF_MEMORY;

-  /* Multiple requests are allowed with this connection */
-  connkeep(conn, "SMB default");
+  /* Do not reuse SMB connections across different shares */
+  connclose(conn, "SMB shares are not verified for reuse");

   /* Parse the username, domain, and password */
   slash = strchr(conn->user, '/');
Description: CVE-2026-6429 - Clear credentials better on HTTP redirect
 When asked to both use a .netrc file for credentials and to follow HTTP
 redirects, libcurl could leak the password used for the first host to
 the followed-to host under certain circumstances. This backport replaces
 the old port/scheme-only comparison with a full same-origin check
 (scheme + host + port) and also clears credentials when they came from
 .netrc (no explicit username set), preventing credential leakage to
 unrelated hosts on redirect.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/curl/curl/commit/b4024bf808bd558026fdc6096e8457f199ace306
Author: Daniel Stenberg <daniel@haxx.se>
Last-Update: 2026-05-02

